{"title_page": "Local quantum field theory", "text_new": "The '''Haag\u2013Kastler [[axiomatic framework]]''' for [[quantum field theory]], introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Haag|authorlink=Rudolf Haag|last2=Kastler|author2-link=Daniel Kastler|year=1964}}, is an application to '''local quantum physics''' of [[C*-algebra]] theory. Because of this it is also known as '''algebraic quantum field theory''' ('''AQFT'''). The axioms are stated in terms of an algebra given for every open set in [[Minkowski space]], and mappings between those.\n\n==Overview<!--'Isotony' redirects here-->==\nLet '''Mink''' be the [[category theory|category]] of [[open subset]]s of Minkowski space M with [[inclusion map]]s as [[morphism]]s. We are given a [[covariant functor]] <math>\\mathcal{A}</math> from '''Mink''' to '''uC*alg''', the category of [[unital algebra|unital]] C* algebras, such that every morphism in '''Mink''' maps to a [[monomorphism]] in '''uC*alg''' ('''isotony'''<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->).\n\nThe [[Poincar\u00e9 group]] acts [[continuity (topology)|continuously]] on '''Mink'''. There exists a [[pullback]] of this [[Group action (mathematics)|action]], which is continuous in the [[norm topology]] of <math>\\mathcal{A}(M)</math> ([[Poincar\u00e9 covariance]]).\n\nMinkowski space has a [[causal structure]]. If an [[open set]] ''V'' lies in the [[causal complement]] of an open set ''U'', then the [[Image (mathematics)|image]] of the maps\n\n:<math>\\mathcal{A}(i_{U,U\\cup V})</math>\n\nand\n\n:<math>\\mathcal{A}(i_{V,U\\cup V})</math>\n\n[[Commutative operation|commute]] (spacelike commutativity). If <math>\\bar{U}</math> is the [[causal completion]] of an open set ''U'', then <math>\\mathcal{A}(i_{U,\\bar{U}})</math> is an [[isomorphism]] (primitive causality).\n\nA [[state (functional analysis)|state]] with respect to a C*-algebra is a [[positive linear functional]] over it with unit [[norm (mathematics)|norm]]. If we have a state over <math>\\mathcal{A}(M)</math>, we can take the \"[[partial trace]]\" to get states associated with <math>\\mathcal{A}(U)</math> for each open set via the [[net (mathematics)|net]] [[monomorphism]]. The states over the open sets form a [[presheaf]] structure.\n\nAccording to the [[GNS construction]], for each state, we can associate a [[Hilbert space]] [[group representation|representation]] of <math>\\mathcal{A}(M).</math> [[Pure state]]s correspond to [[irreducible representation]]s and [[Mixed state (physics)|mixed state]]s correspond to [[reducible representation]]s. Each irreducible representation (up to [[Equivalence relation|equivalence]]) is called a [[superselection sector]]. We assume there is a pure state called the [[vacuum]] such that the Hilbert space associated with it is a [[unitary representation]] of the [[Poincar\u00e9 group]] compatible with the Poincar\u00e9 covariance of the net such that if we look at the [[Poincar\u00e9 algebra]], the spectrum with respect to [[energy-momentum 4-vector|energy-momentum]] (corresponding to [[Poincare group|spacetime translation]]s) lies on and in the positive [[light cone]]. This is the vacuum sector.\n\nMore recently, the approach has been further implemented to include an algebraic version of [[quantum field theory in curved spacetime]]. Indeed, the viewpoint of local quantum physics is in particular suitable to generalize the [[renormalization]] procedure to the theory of quantum fields developed on curved backgrounds. Several rigorous results concerning QFT in presence of a [[black hole]] have been obtained.\n\n== List of researchers in local quantum field theory ==\n* [[Detlev Buchholz]]\n* [[Rudolf Haag]]\n* [[Daniel Kastler]]\n* [[Karl-Henning Rehren]]\n* [[Bert Schroer]]\n* [[Robert Wald]]\n* [[:de:Klaus Fredenhagen|Klaus Fredenhagen]]\n\n== References ==\n\n*{{Citation | last1=Haag | first1=Rudolf | last2=Kastler | first2=Daniel | title=An algebraic approach to quantum field theory | doi=10.1063/1.1704187 | mr=0165864  | year=1964 | journal=[[Journal of Mathematical Physics]] | issn=0022-2488 | volume=5 | pages=848\u2013861|bibcode = 1964JMP.....5..848H }}\n*{{Citation | last1=Haag | first1=Rudolf | title=Local quantum physics | origyear=1992 | publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] | location=Berlin, New York | edition=2nd | series=Texts and Monographs in Physics | isbn=978-3-540-61451-7 | mr=1405610  | year=1996}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lqp2.org Local Quantum Physics Crossroads 2.0] \u2013 A network of scientists working on local quantum physics\n* [http://www.lqp2.org/faceted-paper-view Papers] \u2013 A database of preprints on algebraic QFT\n* [http://unith.desy.de/research/aqft/ Algebraic Quantum Field Theory] \u2013 AQFT resources at the University of Hamburg\n\n{{Quantum field theories}}\n\n[[Category:Quantum field theory]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Haag\u2013Kastler [[axiomatic framework]]''' for [[quantum field theory]], introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Haag|authorlink=Rudolf Haag|last2=Kastler|author2-link=Daniel Kastler|year=1964}}, is an application to '''local quantum physics''' of [[C*-algebra]] theory. Because of this it is also known as '''algebraic quantum field theory''' ('''AQFT'''). The axioms are stated in terms of an algebra given for every open set in [[Minkowski space]], and mappings between those.\n\n==Overview<!--'Isotony' redirects here-->==\nLet '''Mink''' be the [[category theory|category]] of [[open subset]]s of Minkowski space M with [[inclusion map]]s as [[morphism]]s. We are given a [[covariant functor]] <math>\\mathcal{A}</math> from '''Mink''' to '''uC*alg''', the category of [[unital algebra|unital]] C* algebras, such that every morphism in '''Mink''' maps to a [[monomorphism]] in '''uC*alg''' ('''isotony'''<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->).\n\nThe [[Poincar\u00e9 group]] acts [[continuity (topology)|continuously]] on '''Mink'''. There exists a [[pullback]] of this [[Group action (mathematics)|action]], which is continuous in the [[norm topology]] of <math>\\mathcal{A}(M)</math> ([[Poincar\u00e9 covariance]]).\n\nMinkowski space has a [[causal structure]]. If an [[open set]] ''V'' lies in the [[causal complement]] of an open set ''U'', then the [[Image (mathematics)|image]] of the maps\n\n:<math>\\mathcal{A}(i_{U,U\\cup V})</math>\n\nand\n\n:<math>\\mathcal{A}(i_{V,U\\cup V})</math>\n\n[[Commutative operation|commute]] (spacelike commutativity). If <math>\\bar{U}</math> is the [[causal completion]] of an open set ''U'', then <math>\\mathcal{A}(i_{U,\\bar{U}})</math> is an [[isomorphism]] (primitive causality).\n\nA [[state (functional analysis)|state]] with respect to a C*-algebra is a [[positive linear functional]] over it with unit [[norm (mathematics)|norm]]. If we have a state over <math>\\mathcal{A}(M)</math>, we can take the \"[[partial trace]]\" to get states associated with <math>\\mathcal{A}(U)</math> for each open set via the [[net (mathematics)|net]] [[monomorphism]]. The states over the open sets form a [[presheaf]] structure.\n\nAccording to the [[GNS construction]], for each state, we can associate a [[Hilbert space]] [[group representation|representation]] of <math>\\mathcal{A}(M).</math> [[Pure state]]s correspond to [[irreducible representation]]s and [[Mixed state (physics)|mixed state]]s correspond to [[reducible representation]]s. Each irreducible (up to [[Equivalence relation|equivalence]]) is called a [[superselection sector]]. We assume there is a pure state called the [[vacuum]] such that the Hilbert space associated with it is a [[unitary representation]] of the [[Poincar\u00e9 group]] compatible with the Poincar\u00e9 covariance of the net such that if we look at the [[Poincar\u00e9 algebra]], the spectrum with respect to [[energy-momentum 4-vector|energy-momentum]] (corresponding to [[Poincare group|spacetime translation]]s) lies on and in the positive [[light cone]]. This is the vacuum sector.\n\nMore recently, the approach has been further implemented to include an algebraic version of [[quantum field theory in curved spacetime]]. Indeed, the viewpoint of local quantum physics is in particular suitable to generalize the [[renormalization]] procedure to the theory of quantum fields developed on curved backgrounds. Several rigorous results concerning QFT in presence of a [[black hole]] have been obtained.\n\n== List of researchers in local quantum field theory ==\n* [[Detlev Buchholz]]\n* [[Rudolf Haag]]\n* [[Daniel Kastler]]\n* [[Karl-Henning Rehren]]\n* [[Bert Schroer]]\n* [[Robert Wald]]\n* [[:de:Klaus Fredenhagen|Klaus Fredenhagen]]\n\n== References ==\n\n*{{Citation | last1=Haag | first1=Rudolf | last2=Kastler | first2=Daniel | title=An algebraic approach to quantum field theory | doi=10.1063/1.1704187 | mr=0165864  | year=1964 | journal=[[Journal of Mathematical Physics]] | issn=0022-2488 | volume=5 | pages=848\u2013861|bibcode = 1964JMP.....5..848H }}\n*{{Citation | last1=Haag | first1=Rudolf | title=Local quantum physics | origyear=1992 | publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] | location=Berlin, New York | edition=2nd | series=Texts and Monographs in Physics | isbn=978-3-540-61451-7 | mr=1405610  | year=1996}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lqp2.org Local Quantum Physics Crossroads 2.0] \u2013 A network of scientists working on local quantum physics\n* [http://www.lqp2.org/faceted-paper-view Papers] \u2013 A database of preprints on algebraic QFT\n* [http://unith.desy.de/research/aqft/ Algebraic Quantum Field Theory] \u2013 AQFT resources at the University of Hamburg\n\n{{Quantum field theories}}\n\n[[Category:Quantum field theory]]\n", "name_user": "Shoy.ouseph", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added the missing word 'representation' after 'irreducible'.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_quantum_field_theory"}
{"title_page": "YouTube Rewind", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = YouTube Rewind\n| image                    = YouTube Rewind 2018 Logo.jpg\n| genre                    = [[Year-in-review]], [[Mashup (video)|video mashup]], [[Mashup (music)|music mashup]]\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n*YouTube<ref name=\"youtubepotlight2010\" /><ref name=\"youtubetrends2010\" /> <small>(2010)</small>\n*YouTube, Seedwell<ref name=seedwell2012/> <small>(2012)</small>\n*YouTube, Portal A Interactive<ref name=\"portala2013\" /><ref name=\"portala2014\" /><ref name=\"portala2015\" /><ref name=\"portalavideos\" /> <small>(2011 & 2013\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Peter Furia <small>(2012)</small>\n*Kai Hasson <small>(2011, 2013\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| opentheme                = [[The Hood Internet]] \u2013 mashup music\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Avicii]] \u2013 \"[[Levels (Avicii song)|Levels]]\"<ref name=\"portala2015\" /><ref name=\"2011ytr\" /> <small>(2011, 2015)</small>\n*Jeff Kite <small>(2012)</small><ref name=seedwell2012/>\n*Jordan Roseman aka [[DJ Earworm]] <small>(2013\u20132014)</small><ref name=\"portala2013\" /><ref name=\"portala2014\" />\n*The Hood Internet <small>(2015\u2013present)</small><ref name=\"portala2015\" />}}\n[[Major Lazer]] (original remix) <small>(2016)</small>\n[[BTS (band)|BTS]] \u2013 [[Idol (BTS song)|Idol]] (2018)\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 2\n| num_episodes             = 10\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Lee Hunter, Michael Rucker, Kevin Allocca, Dom Elliott<ref name=seedwell2012/> <small>(2012)</small>\n*Nate Houghteling, Zach Blume <small>(2013\u2013present)</small><ref name=\"portala2013\" /><ref name=\"portala2014\" /><ref name=\"portala2015\" />\n*Kai Hasson<ref name=\"portala2015\" /> <small>(2014\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Jeffrey Sabin-Matsumoto, Finley Wise <small>(2011, 2013\u2013present)</small>\n*Michael Rucker, Peter Furia, Beau Lewis <small>(2012)</small>\n}}\n| runtime                  = 1\u20138 minutes\n| company                  = YouTube, LLC, Portal A Interactive\n| distributor              = YouTube, LLC\n| network                  = YouTube, LLC\n| picture_format           = [[1080p]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereophonic]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|December 12, 2010}}<ref name=\"youtubetrends2010\" />\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://www.youtube.com/\n| website_title            = YouTube\n| production_website       = http://portal-a.com/\n| production_website_title = Portal A Interactive\n}}\n\n'''''YouTube Rewind''''' (stylized as '''''YouTube \u042fEWIND''''') is a video series produced and created by [[YouTube]] and [[Portal A Interactive]]. These videos are an overview and a recap of each year's [[viral video]]s, events, trends, and music.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Movies |date=December 9, 2015 |title=YouTube 'Rewind' Video Proves Nothing Is Mainstream Anymore |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/12/youtube-rewind-mainstream/ |url-status=live |journal=Wired |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514063414/http://www.wired.com/2015/12/youtube-rewind-mainstream/ |archive-date=May 14, 2016 |access-date=May 14, 2016}}</ref> Each year, the number of YouTube personalities featured has increased. The series' annual installments are uploaded onto [[YouTube (channel)|YouTube's official channel]].\n\nThe 2018 episode of ''YouTube Rewind'', ''[[YouTube Rewind 2018: Everyone Controls Rewind]]'', received near universal disdain from critics, YouTubers, and viewers alike garnering over 10 million dislikes in its first two weeks, becoming [[List of most-disliked YouTube videos|the most disliked video of all time on YouTube]]. The latest episode, ''[[YouTube Rewind 2019: For the Record]]'', received negative reactions from fans, citing that it was better than the previous installment, but was criticized due to being uncreative and lacking in energy compared to previous episodes of ''Rewind''.{{dubious|date=December 2019}}\n\n==History==\nThe first ''Rewind'' was created by YouTube in 2010 and featured a Top 50 list of the most popular YouTube videos for that year. In 2010, YouTube had started to create and produce ''Rewind'' videos with the help of Seedwell and Portal A Interactive.<ref name=\"seedwell2012\">{{Cite web |url=http://seedwell.com/blog/2012/12/seedwell-produces-rewind-youtube-style-2012-feat-psy-wote-and-star-studded-youtube-celebrity-cast/ |title=SeedwellProduces \"Rewind YouTube Style 2012and Star-Studded YouTube Celebrity Cast |date=December 17, 2012 |website=Seedwell Blog |publisher=Seedwell Creative Studio |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228012720/http://seedwell.com/blog/2012/12/seedwell-produces-rewind-youtube-style-2012-feat-psy-wote-and-star-studded-youtube-celebrity-cast/ |archive-date=February 28, 2016 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"portalavideos\">{{Cite web |url=http://theinspirationroom.com/daily/tag/portal-a-interactive/ |title=Portal A Interactive |website=Inspiration Room |publisher=The Inspiration Room |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306052613/http://theinspirationroom.com/daily/tag/portal-a-interactive/ |archive-date=March 6, 2016 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"youtube10to15\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/YouTube/searchquery=YouTube+Rewind |title=YouTube Spotlight Rewind |website=YouTube |publisher=YouTube, LLC |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507210934/https://www.youtube.com/user/YouTube/searchquery%3DYouTube%2BRewind |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> From 2011 onward, the ''YouTube Rewind'' videos have only been uploaded to the [[YouTube Spotlight]] channel now known as just YouTube, with additional \"behind-the-scenes\" content.<ref name=\"youtube10to15\" />\n\n===2010===\nOn December 13, 2010, the first ''YouTube Rewind'' was uploaded, titled \"2010 YouTube Rewind: Year in Review\". It featured the top 10 most popular videos on YouTube for the preceding year. It was uploaded on two channels: YouTube Trends on the first day,<ref name=\"youtubetrends2010\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RUzLhHH7gHg |title=YouTube Rewind 2010: Year in Review |date=December 12, 2010 |website=YouTube |publisher=YouTube, LLC |format=Video |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215005935/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RUzLhHH7gHg |archive-date=December 15, 2010 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> and YouTube Spotlight on the second.<ref name=\"youtubepotlight2010\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFnXm6cjGwU |title=YouTube Rewind 2010: Year in Review |date=December 13, 2010 |website=YouTube |publisher=YouTube, LCC |format=Video |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329040332/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFnXm6cjGwU |archive-date=March 29, 2016 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\nOn December 20, 2011, \"YouTube Rewind 2011\" was uploaded.<ref name=\"portalavideos\" /><ref name=\"2011ytr\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SmnkYyHQqNs |title=YouTube Rewind 2011 |website=YouTube (description) |publisher=YouTube, LLC |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307145847/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SmnkYyHQqNs |archive-date=March 7, 2016 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> It was created and produced by YouTube and Portal A Interactive,<ref name=\"portalavideos\" /> and features [[Rebecca Black]] as the host. Her music video \"[[Friday (Rebecca Black song)|Friday]]\" had become a viral video in March 2011.<ref name=\"portalavideos\" /><ref name=\"mashableachive\">{{Cite news |url=http://mashable.com/2011/03/16/rebecca-black-youtube/ |title=How Rebecca Black Became a YouTube Sensation |last=Wasserman, Todd |date=March 24, 2011 |work=[[Mashable]] |access-date=March 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113124111/http://mashable.com/2011/03/16/rebecca-black-youtube/#DZIM1XHG1Eqt |archive-date=January 13, 2016}}</ref> Like last year, it featured another top 10 most popular videos on YouTube for the year.<ref name=\"youtube10to15\" />\n\n===2012===\nIn 2012, YouTube's ''Rewind'' videos changed to featuring several popular [[List of YouTubers|YouTubers]]; the most popular music, videos, and [[mashup (video)|videos]]; [[breaking news]]; and internet memes from the year. \n\nOn December 17, 2012, \"Rewind YouTube Style 2012\", referencing \"[[Gangnam Style]]\", was uploaded to YouTube Spotlight.<ref name=\"rewind2012\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iCkYw3cRwLo |title=Rewind YouTube Style 2012 |date=December 17, 2011 |website=YouTube |publisher=YouTube LLC |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160226151724/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iCkYw3cRwLo |archive-date=February 26, 2016 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> It was created and produced by YouTube and Seedwill.<ref name=seedwell2012/>\n\n===2013===\n[[File:YouTube Rewind Logo (2017 to Present).svg|100px|thumb|left|The YouTube Rewind button was introduced in 2013.]]\nOn December 11, 2013, \"YouTube Rewind: What Does 2013 Say?\", referencing \"[[The Fox (What Does the Fox Say?)]]\", was uploaded to YouTube Spotlight.<ref name=\"portala2013\">{{Cite web |url=http://portal-a.com/rewind/ |title=REWIND 2013: WhaYouTube Say? |date=December 10, 2013 |website=Portal A News |publisher=Portal A Interactive |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404015730/http://portal-a.com/rewind/ |archive-date=April 4, 2016 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> The video also made prominent use of [[PSY]]'s popularising \"Gentleman\", however following a copyright claim from the artist, the audio on the original video was remixed in 2015 to no longer include the song. The video was created and produced by YouTube and Portal A Interactive.<ref name=\"portala2013\" /> This was the first year that the YouTube Rewind Button was used; otherwise, it was very similar in style to the 2012 video. [[DJ Earworm]] mashed up six popular songs from the year. [[Jimmy Fallon]] and [[The Roots]] from ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' made guest appearances.<ref name=\"portala2013\" /> Popular YouTuber PewDiePie made his first appearance on a YouTube Rewind in the 2013 rewind.\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===2014===\nOn December 9, 2014,<ref name=\"portala2014\">{{Cite web |url=http://portal-a.com/rewind2014/ |title=#YouTubeRewind: Turn Down for 2014 |date=December 9, 2014 |website=Portal A News |publisher=Portal A Interactive |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308021125/http://portal-a.com/rewind2014/ |archive-date=March 8, 2016 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> \"YouTube Rewind: Turn Down for 2014\", referencing \"[[Turn Down for What]]\", was uploaded to YouTube Spotlight. It was again created and produced by YouTube and Portal A Interactive. Over 10 songs were mashed together by DJ Earworm<ref name=\"portala2014\" /><ref name=\"ytr2014\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zKx2B8WCQuw |title=YouTube Rewind: Turn Down for 2014 |website=YouTube |publisher=YouTube, LLC |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209180947/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zKx2B8WCQuw |archive-date=December 9, 2014 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> for the video.<ref name=\"portala2014\" /> The video was not structured around songs, as in previous years. More internet memes and trends were used alongside the music. Its main features were the YouTube Rewind Button flag, with which YouTubers and characters run from the beginning of the video all the way to the end. The flag was run through the sets of ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' by [[Big Bird]]; ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]'' by [[Conan O'Brien]], running through his own with [[Freddie Wong]] acting as the host' and ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]'', by [[Robby Novak|Kid President]]. The actual Rewind Button was not shown until the end of the video.<ref name=\"ytr2014\" />\n\n===2015===\nOn December 9, 2015,<ref name=\"portala2015\">{{Cite web |url=http://portal-a.com/rewind2015/ |title=#YouTubeRewind: Now Watch Me 2015 |date=December 9, 2015 |website=Portal A News |publisher=Portal A Interactive |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330221625/https://www.portal-a.com/rewind2015/ |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |access-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> \"YouTube Rewind: Now Watch Me 2015\", referencing \"[[Watch Me (Whip/Nae Nae)|Watch Me]]\", was uploaded to the YouTube Spotlight channel. It was again created and produced by YouTube and Portal A Interactive. It was the first one to feature a hashtag; #YouTubeRewind.<ref name=\"portala2015\" /><ref name=\"youtube10to15\" /> The video heavily incorporated previous years of YouTube due to 2015 being the website's 10th anniversary.<ref name=\"firstyoutubevideo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/04/23/youtube-turns-10-today-this-was-its-first-ever-video.html |title=YouTube turns 10 today. This was its first ever video |last=Giuliano |first=Karissa |date=February 14, 2015 |access-date=March 1, 2016 |publisher=CNBC LLC, Division of NBCUniversal |agency=CNBC}}</ref> The music mashup was composed by [[The Hood Internet]] and include songs like [[Lean On]] by [[Major Lazer]] and [[DJ Snake]], [[Can't Feel My Face]] by [[The Weeknd]], and [[What Do You Mean?]] by [[Justin Bieber]]. Additionally, [[Avicii]] composed an original [[Remix#Electronic music|remix]] for the video.<ref name=\"portala2015\" /><ref name=\"youtube10to15\" /> The video featured more [[gamer]]s than previous years, such as YouTube personalities [[Markiplier]] and Captainsparklez, with a segment set up to resemble the ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's (series)|Five Nights at Freddy's]]'', an [[Indie game|indie]], [[survival horror]], [[Point-and-click game|point-and-click]] [[video game]] that has gained recognition since its first release in August 2014. The Rewind Button and logo were shown throughout the video. Its main appearance was with [[PewDiePie]] and [[Zoella|Zoe Sugg]] about halfway through the video. They appeared next to a scoreboard with two dates of December 9, 2015. The scoreboard referenced [[Back to the Future Part II]] which was set in 2015. Zoe changes one scoreboard date back to February 14, 2005, leaving the other at December 9, 2015. Afterwards Felix \"[[brofist]]s\" the rewind button, triggering the video to show viral videos and memes from 2015 back to 2005. After the credits, the [[Fine Brothers]] were shown arguing about whether PewDiePie was in the video.<ref name=\"youtube10to15\" />\n\n===2016===\nOn December 7, 2016,<ref name=\"YTRewind2016\">{{Citation |last=YouTube Spotlight |title=YouTube Rewind: The Ultimate 2016 Challenge {{!}} #YouTubeRewind |date=December 7, 2016 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_GuOjXYl5ew |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504231607/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_GuOjXYl5ew |access-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-date=May 4, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> \"YouTube Rewind: The Ultimate 2016 Challenge\", referencing the increasing number of [[List of Internet phenomena#Challenges|challenges]] that took place in 2016, was uploaded to the YouTube Spotlight channel.  It was again created and produced by YouTube and Portal A Interactive. Music was developed by The Hood Internet with an original remix by Major Lazer. The video begins with [[Dwayne Johnson]] showing a miniature Rewind button, and YouTube personalities hunting for 'Rewind' symbols in the style of ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]''. The video also references objects being crushed by a [[hydraulic press]], Hodor from ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', the water-bottle flip challenge and the [[Dab (dance)|dabbing]] dance move. The video also references songs like: [[Work from Home|Work From Home]] by [[Fifth Harmony]], [[Closer (The Chainsmokers song)|Closer]] by [[The Chainsmokers]]. The video ends [[James Corden]] and other personalities in a car, in reference to the [[Carpool Karaoke]] segments from ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden|The Late Late Show]]''.\n\n===2017===\nOn December 6, 2017, \"YouTube Rewind: The Shape of 2017\", referencing the song \"[[Shape of You]]\" by [[Ed Sheeran]], and was uploaded to the YouTube Spotlight channel.\n\n''The Shape of 2017'' received mixed reviews from critics, YouTubers,<ref>[[Emma Blackery]] (December 8, 2017). {{youtube|jNsWYq7Bo9E|YouTube Rewind: The Truth (Why I'm saying NO next year)}}.</ref> and viewers alike following its release. Some of the various criticisms were directed at its overuse of memes,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.player.one/youtube-rewind-2017-122153 |title=YouTube Rewind 2017 Ignores Adpocalypse For Paul Brothers And Paint |last=Asarch |first=Steven |date=July 6, 2017 |website=player.one |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124436/https://www.player.one/youtube-rewind-2017-122153 |archive-date=December 9, 2018 |access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref> and the notable exclusion of [[PewDiePie]] for [[PewDiePie#Controversial videos, network drop and streaming (2017)|controversies earlier in the year]].<ref>[[PewDiePie]] (December 7, 2017). {{youtube|w4AImq08j9o|Why I'm not in YouTube Rewind 2017}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/16/171216.html |title=PewDiePie 'not salty' at YouTube for not including him in 2017 Rewind |website=www.bizcommunity.com |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206102243/http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/16/171216.html |archive-date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://medium.com/@julia.alexander/youtube-review-2017-you-cant-ignore-pewdiepie-dfe47336e8a0 |title=YouTube Rewind 2017: You can't ignore PewDiePie |last=Alexander |first=Julia |date=December 10, 2017 |website=Julia Alexander |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206192533/https://medium.com/@julia.alexander/youtube-review-2017-you-cant-ignore-pewdiepie-dfe47336e8a0 |archive-date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/pewdiepie-youtuber-explains-sad-absence-youtube-rewind-2017-2170398 |title=World's most popular YouTuber explains \"sad\" absence from YouTube Rewind 2017 |last=Connick |first=Tom |date=December 11, 2017 |website=NME |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206062246/https://www.nme.com/news/tv/pewdiepie-youtuber-explains-sad-absence-youtube-rewind-2017-2170398 |archive-date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> \n\nTo date, it has received 4.09 million likes, making it [[List of most-liked YouTube videos#Non-music videos|9th most liked non-music YouTube video of all time]]. It also received significantly more dislikes than the previous years (excluding 2011), at 2.2 million dislikes (as of 2020), making it the [[List of most-disliked YouTube videos|20th most disliked YouTube video of all time]].<!--It also has 1.3 out of 10 on [[iMDB]], making it the worst-rated program in the history of the website.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://canyonechoes.org/6831/just-for-fun/youtube-rewind-2017-the-worst-of-all/ |title=YouTube Rewind 2017 \u2013 The Worst of All |last=Nguyen |first=Austin |last2=Nguyen |first2=Austin |date=December 12, 2017 |website=Canyon Echoes |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11955753 |title=The 2017 YouTube Rewind video is a mess |date=December 7, 2017 |work=NZ Herald |access-date=December 6, 2018 |language=en-NZ |issn=1170-0777}}</ref>-->\n\n===2018=== \n{{Main|YouTube Rewind 2018: Everyone Controls Rewind}}\nWorst rewind ever\n\n===2019===\n{{main|YouTube Rewind 2019: For the Record}}\n\nOn December 5, 2019, \"''YouTube Rewind 2019: For the Record\"'' was released. The 2019 edition returned to a format more reminiscent of the early iterations of the series, featuring a montage of the top videos of 2019, divided into several themed countdowns based on statistics and trends. Kevin Allocca, YouTube's head of culture and trends, explained that the video was intended to be more reflective of the year's trends, acknowledging that it was becoming more difficult for the previous format to \"authentically represent\" the community's overall experience.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/12/5/20987248/youtube-rewind-2019-pewdiepie-shane-dawson-jeffree-star-james-charles-tati-westbrook |title=PewDiePie makes his return to YouTube Rewind after two years of controversy |last=Alexander |first=Julia |date=2019-12-05 |website=[[The Verge]] |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205205504/https://www.theverge.com/2019/12/5/20987248/youtube-rewind-2019-pewdiepie-shane-dawson-jeffree-star-james-charles-tati-westbrook |archive-date=December 5, 2019 |access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> The video has been criticized as coming off as \u201cpassive-aggressive\u201d towards consumers, or \"lazy\" as it does not have the same level of production as the previous rewinds and was noted as being akin to [[WatchMojo.com|WatchMojo]] videos. Many also felt the new format lacked energy and a \u201csoul,\u201d saying that it showed that YouTube was being openly more corporate.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/12/05/youtube-rewind-2019-branded-lazy-goes-back-roots-compilation-11279043/ |title=YouTube Rewind 2019 branded 'lazy' as it goes back to its roots for compilation |last=Griffin |first=Louise |date=5 December 2019 |access-date=6 December 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205230625/https://metro.co.uk/2019/12/05/youtube-rewind-2019-branded-lazy-goes-back-roots-compilation-11279043/ |archive-date=December 5, 2019 |website=Metro.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/youtube-rewind-2019-video-reactions-2019-12 |title=The internet is roasting YouTube's 'Rewind 2019' video, with people calling it lazy and low-budget |last=Leskin |first=Paige |access-date=2019-12-06 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206000846/https://www.businessinsider.com/youtube-rewind-2019-video-reactions-2019-12 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |website=[[Business Insider]]}}</ref>\nHowever, many saw improvement with casting choices in some areas, particularly with the inclusion of [[PewDiePie|Felix \"PewDiePie\" Kjellberg]], who was absent in previous Rewinds.<ref name=\"Alexander\" />\nSimilarly to last year, some viewers criticized the site for not honouring the deaths of famous people on the site such as [[Etika|Desmond \"Etika\" Amofah]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://in.mashable.com/culture/9173/youtube-rewind-2019-might-be-trying-to-break-last-years-record-for-most-dislikes |title=YouTube Rewind 2019 might be trying to break last years record for most dislikes |access-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206163132/https://in.mashable.com/culture/9173/youtube-rewind-2019-might-be-trying-to-break-last-years-record-for-most-dislikes |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |website=[[Mashable]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/nintendo-community-outraged-over-lack-of-etika-tribute-in-youtube-rewind-1296544 |title=Nintendo community outraged over lack of Etika tribute in Youtube Rewind |website=Dexerto.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/201912